<DOC><DOCNO> AP880806-0036 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-08-06-88 1648EDT</FILEID><FIRST>r a AM-BRF--SubCommission     08-06 0128</FIRST><SECOND>AM-BRF--Sub Commission,0131</SECOND><HEAD>USS San Juan Joins Fleet in Connecticut Ceremony</HEAD><DATELINE>NEW LONDON, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   The USS San Juan, the Navy's newestsubmarine, was commissioned Saturday during a ceremony picketed byanti-nuclear weapons demonstrators.   The nuclear attack sub, built by General Dynamics Corp., is thethird U.S. Navy ship to bear the name San Juan, the capital ofPuerto Rico.   The vessel is 360 feet long, 33 feet wide and displaces about6,900 tons of water when submerged. A so-called Los Angeles-classsub, the San Juan is designed to hunt and destroy enemy submarines.   About 10 anti-nuclear weapons opponents staged a demonstrationoutside the submarine base to protest the commissioning. There wereno arrests, police said.   Puerto Rico territorial Gov. Rafael Hernandez Colon attended theceremony.</TEXT></DOC>